1219":"1180–1219","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1267":"1267","1242":"1242","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","before 1219":"before 1219","1308":"1308","1219":"1219","1180":"1180","London, London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","Ireland":"Ireland","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Woodchurch, Kent, England":"Woodchurch, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Harvey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Hervei</i>, also found as <i>Herveu</i>, <i>Hervé</i>, and <i>Hervi</i>. The name <i>Herveu</i> or <i>Herv(e)i</i> was borne by a number of Bretons at the Norman Conquest and, as such, represents a French form of the Old Breton name <i>Hoiearnviu</i> or <i>Hærviu</i> (see   Herve  ). Among Normans <i>Herve(i)</i> or <i>Herv(e)i</i> was also a French form of ancient Germanic <i>Hariwic</i>, <i>Herewic</i> (from <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>wīg</i> ‘war’), with intervocalic /w/ becoming /v/ in Old French. The Breton and ancient Germanic names were commonly Latinized as <i>Herve(i)us</i> and <i>Hervic(i)us</i> respectively but, since their most common vernacular forms in Old French were indistinguishable, the Latin forms were also sometimes interchangeable, especially <i>Herveus</i>.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hAirmheadhaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Airmheadhach</i>’, a personal name probably meaning ‘esteemed’. It seems to be a derivative of <i>Airmheadh</i>, the name borne by a mythological physician.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEarchaidh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Earchadh</i>’, a personal name of uncertain origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Arvey","meanings":["English: variant of   Harvey  ."]},{"name":"Harvie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Harvey  ."]},{"name":"Herve","meanings":["Breton (<b>Hervé</b>): from the Old Breton personal name <i>Hoiearnviu</i>, composed of the elements <i>hoiarn</i> ‘iron’ and <i>viu</i> ‘blazing’, or <i>Hærviu</i>, with the first element meaning ‘battle’ or ‘fort’.","French (<b>Hervé</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Hariwig</i>, composed of the elements <i>hari</i> ‘army’ and <i>wig</i> ‘battle’. Compare   Harvey  ."]},{"name":"Hervey","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Harvey  ."]},{"name":"Havey","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Harvey  , although some instances in the historical records may be spelling errors."]},{"name":"Harvison","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): patronymic from the personal name   Harvey   + ‘son’."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Kyong, Kyong Suk, Young, Chae, Chi Young, Hang, Kil, Rin, Sang Hun, Chang, Chong, Insoo, Kum, Sun Young, Yom, Young Hwan.  Cambodian Kiwan, Oeurn, Phoeun, Pich, Saroeuth, Seung, Sophath, Sophea, Yoeun, Phan, Son.  Indian Shanti, Harendra.","Indian (Uttar Pradesh): Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>om</i>, the Hindu sacred and mystic syllable uttered at the beginning of prayers.","Cambodian: written ឱម, corresponding to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":5,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":40,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Anne Harvey of Woodchurch was born in 1219, in London, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Walter Harvey, was 39 and her mother, Lady Mary Dering, was 39. She married Sir Thomas Clarke of Woodchurch in 1240, in Woodchurch, Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1267, in Woodchurch, Kent, England, at the age of 48, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1219–1267":"1219–1267","1216–1286":"1216–1286","1242–1308":"1242–1308","1180–1272":"1180–1272","1180–1219":"1180–1219","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1267":"1267","1242":"1242","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","before 1219":"enne 1219","1308":"1308","1219":"1219","1180":"1180","London, London, England":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ireland":"Iirimaa","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Woodchurch, Kent, England":"Woodchurch, Kent, England"},"fi":{"1219–1267":"1219–1267","1216–1286":"1216–1286","1242–130